var tafsirData_10 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Ra.": "These are disjointed Arabic letters that appear at the beginning of some Quranic chapters. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. They serve to capture the attention of the listener and demonstrate that the Quran, despite being composed of the same letters Arabs use daily, is inimitable and miraculous in its composition.",
    "These are the verses of the Book,": "This refers to the Quran itself—the divine scripture sent down from Allah. The word 'verses' (ayat) also means 'signs,' indicating that each verse is a sign pointing to Allah's truth and guidance.",
    "rich in wisdom.": "The Quran is filled with profound wisdom, containing guidance for all aspects of life—spiritual, moral, social, and practical. It distinguishes between right and wrong, truth and falsehood, and provides solutions to humanity's problems."
  },
  2: {
    "Is it astonishing to people that We have sent revelation to a man from among themselves,": "Allah questions why people find it strange that He chose a human being—someone they know and live among—to receive His message. This was a common objection: 'Why would Allah send a human messenger instead of an angel?' But sending a human messenger makes perfect sense because humans can relate to, learn from, and follow another human's example. The Prophet Muhammad ﷺ was known among his people for his honesty and trustworthiness even before prophethood.",
    "˹instructing him,˺ \"Warn humanity": "The messenger's primary task includes warning people about the consequences of disbelief, sin, and turning away from Allah. This warning is an act of mercy—like warning someone about danger ahead on their path.",
    "and give good news to the believers that they will have an honourable status with their Lord.\"?": "Along with warnings come glad tidings for those who believe. The 'honourable status' (qadam sidq) refers to a firm footing, a high rank, and accumulated good deeds that precede them to Paradise. Their faith and righteous actions have already secured them a noble position with Allah.",
    "Yet the disbelievers said, \"Indeed, this ˹man˺ is clearly a magician!\"": "Despite witnessing the Prophet's ﷺ noble character and the Quran's miraculous nature, the disbelievers dismissed him as a magician. This was their way of explaining away the Quran's powerful effect on hearts without accepting its divine origin. They could not deny its impact, so they attributed it to magic—a baseless accusation born from arrogance."
  },
  3: {
    "Surely your Lord is Allah Who created the heavens and the earth in six Days,": "Allah is the Creator of everything—the vast heavens with their stars and galaxies, and the earth with all its complexity. He created all of this in six days, though He could have done so instantly. This measured creation teaches us the value of planning and patience. These 'days' are periods of time known to Allah, not necessarily our 24-hour days.",
    "then established Himself on the Throne,": "After creation, Allah rose over His Throne (Al-Arsh) in a manner befitting His majesty—beyond human comprehension. This does not mean He was absent before or that He needs the Throne; rather, it demonstrates His supreme authority and sovereignty over all creation.",
    "conducting every affair.": "Allah manages and directs every matter in the universe—from the movement of galaxies to the growth of a single cell. Nothing happens without His knowledge and will. He sustains all life, sends rain, causes death, gives life, and controls all affairs with perfect wisdom.",
    "None can intercede except by His permission.": "No one—not an angel, prophet, or righteous person—can intercede or plead on behalf of anyone else before Allah without His permission. This refutes the pagan belief that their idols could automatically intercede for them. Intercession belongs to Allah, and He grants permission only to whom He wills and for whom He is pleased.",
    "That is Allah—your Lord, so worship Him ˹alone˺.": "Given Allah's complete sovereignty and control, the logical conclusion is that He alone deserves worship. No created being shares in His power, so no created being deserves any portion of worship.",
    "Will you not then be mindful?": "This is a call to reflection and awareness. After hearing these clear truths about Allah's lordship, will you not take heed, remember, and act accordingly? Being mindful means recognizing Allah's rights and fulfilling our duty to worship Him alone."
  },
  4: {
    "To Him is your return all together.": "Every single person—regardless of status, time, or place—will return to Allah after death. There is no escape from this meeting. All of humanity, from the first person to the last, will be gathered before Him.",
    "Allah's promise is ˹always˺ true.": "Whatever Allah promises will certainly happen. His promise of resurrection, judgment, reward, and punishment is absolutely certain. Unlike human promises that may fail, Allah's word never fails.",
    "Indeed, He originates the creation then resurrects it": "Allah created everything from nothing the first time, and He will bring it all back to life again. The One who created you initially has no difficulty recreating you. This logic appears throughout the Quran: the first creation is proof of the second.",
    "so that He may justly reward those who believe and do good.": "The resurrection exists so that justice can be served. Those who believed in Allah and performed righteous deeds will be rewarded fairly. Their faith and good works will not be lost or forgotten.",
    "But those who disbelieve will have a boiling drink and a painful punishment for their disbelief.": "Those who rejected Allah and His messengers will face severe consequences. They will be given boiling water to drink—a horrific contrast to the cool, refreshing drinks of Paradise. Their punishment is a direct result of their choice to disbelieve despite clear evidence."
  },
  5: {
    "He is the One Who made the sun a radiant source and the moon a reflected light,": "Allah designed the sun to produce its own brilliant light and heat, while the moon reflects light—a scientific fact stated in the Quran over 1400 years ago. The sun blazes with its own energy, while the moon borrows and reflects the sun's light. Both serve humanity in countless ways.",
    "with precisely ordained phases,": "The moon passes through exact, predictable phases—from new moon to full moon and back. These phases follow a precise pattern that never fails, demonstrating Allah's perfect planning and control over celestial bodies.",
    "so that you may know the number of years and calculation ˹of time˺.": "These celestial cycles serve a practical purpose: they allow humans to track time—days, months, and years. The lunar calendar used in Islam is based on the moon's phases, while solar movements mark seasons. This system enables planning for agriculture, travel, worship, and daily life.",
    "Allah did not create all this except for a purpose.": "Nothing in Allah's creation is random, meaningless, or accidental. Every created thing has wisdom behind it. The sun, moon, stars, and all natural phenomena serve specific purposes—both practical and spiritual. Recognizing this purpose leads to recognizing the Creator.",
    "He makes the signs clear for people of knowledge.": "Those who seek knowledge, reflect, and study creation will find clear evidence of Allah's existence, power, and wisdom. The signs are everywhere, but they benefit most those who approach them with open minds and sincere hearts seeking truth."
  },
  6: {
    "Surely in the alternation of the day and the night,": "The consistent succession of day and night—one replacing the other in an endless, reliable cycle—is a profound sign. This alternation enables rest, work, and the sustenance of all life. The balance between daylight and darkness reflects Allah's perfect design.",
    "and in all that Allah has created in the heavens and the earth,": "Beyond the day-night cycle, everything in existence—stars, planets, clouds, mountains, oceans, plants, animals, and microscopic organisms—serves as evidence of the Creator. The diversity, complexity, and harmony of creation all point to one intelligent, powerful Designer.",
    "there are truly signs for those mindful ˹of Him˺.": "These signs benefit most those who have taqwa—consciousness of Allah, reverence for Him, and desire to avoid His displeasure. When someone is mindful of Allah, they see His hand in everything around them. The same sunrise that one person ignores becomes, for the mindful person, a powerful reminder of Allah's majesty."
  },
  7: {
    "Indeed, those who do not expect to meet Us,": "These are people who live as if there is no Day of Judgment, no standing before Allah, and no accountability. They neither hope for meeting Allah (which believers eagerly anticipate) nor fear it. Their denial of the afterlife shapes their entire worldview and behavior.",
    "being pleased and content with this worldly life,": "They have settled for the temporary pleasures of this world and made it their ultimate goal. They find complete satisfaction in worldly pursuits—wealth, status, entertainment—and desire nothing beyond it. This world, with all its limitations, is enough for them.",
    "and who are heedless of Our signs,": "Despite signs everywhere pointing to Allah—in nature, in revelation, in their own souls—they remain oblivious. They see but do not perceive; they hear but do not understand. This heedlessness is willful; they choose to ignore what would disturb their comfortable worldliness."
  },
  8: {
    "they will have the Fire as a home": "Their final dwelling—not a temporary stop but a permanent residence—will be the Hellfire. The word 'home' emphasizes the permanence and the tragic irony: they sought a home in this temporary world and will end up in the worst possible eternal abode.",
    "because of what they have committed.": "This punishment is not arbitrary but is a direct consequence of their choices and actions. They earned this outcome through their disbelief, heedlessness, and the sins they accumulated. Allah's justice ensures that everyone receives exactly what they deserve."
  },
  9: {
    "Surely those who believe and do good,": "True faith is always accompanied by righteous actions. Belief is not merely a claim but manifests in good deeds. These two—faith and action—are inseparable in the Quran, mentioned together repeatedly to emphasize that genuine belief produces righteousness.",
    "their Lord will guide them ˹to Paradise˺ through their faith,": "Their faith serves as a light guiding them—on the Day of Judgment, their faith will illuminate their path to Paradise. Some scholars explain that their faith guided them in this life to good deeds, which then lead them to Paradise. Either way, faith is the key that opens the door to eternal bliss.",
    "rivers will flow under their feet in the Gardens of Bliss,": "Imagine gardens so lush and beautiful that rivers flow beneath them—rivers of pure water, milk, honey, and wine (as described elsewhere in the Quran). The believers will reside in elevated positions with these rivers flowing below, a scene of perfect peace and beauty beyond our imagination."
  },
  10: {
    "in which their prayer will be, \"Glory be to You, O Allah!\"": "In Paradise, the believers will naturally glorify Allah—not out of obligation but out of pure joy and love. Just as breathing comes naturally to us, praising Allah will flow effortlessly from them. 'Subhanaka Allahumma' (Glory be to You, O Allah) will be their constant expression of awe.",
    "and their greeting will be, \"Peace!\"": "The inhabitants of Paradise will greet each other with 'Salam'—peace. There will be no hatred, jealousy, harsh words, or conflict. Peace will characterize every interaction, reflecting the perfect harmony of that blessed abode.",
    "and their closing prayer will be, \"All praise is for Allah—Lord of all worlds!\"": "Their expressions of worship will conclude with 'Alhamdulillahi Rabbil Aalameen'—the same words that open Surah Al-Fatiha. In Paradise, believers will understand fully why all praise belongs to Allah, having experienced His mercy, witnessed His justice, and received His reward. Gratitude will overflow from their hearts."
  },
  11: {
    "If Allah were to hasten evil for people as they wish to hasten good,": "People often pray for good things immediately—health, wealth, success. But sometimes, in moments of anger or frustration, they invoke curses upon themselves or others, or the disbelievers mockingly challenged Allah to send His punishment immediately. If Allah responded to these negative requests as quickly as people wish good things would come, disaster would befall them instantly.",
    "they would have certainly been doomed.": "Had Allah answered every hasty, ill-considered curse or the disbelievers' mocking demands for punishment, humanity would have been destroyed long ago. Allah's delay is mercy, giving people time to repent and return to Him.",
    "But We leave those who do not expect to meet Us to wander blindly in their defiance.": "Allah allows those who deny the afterlife to continue in their rebellion. This is not neglect but a form of test and respite. They wander in their transgression, blind to guidance, thinking they are free when they are actually accumulating sins. Eventually, they will face the consequences they denied."
  },
  12: {
    "Whenever someone is touched by hardship, they cry out to Us, whether lying on their side, sitting, or standing.": "When difficulty strikes—illness, poverty, danger, or loss—people turn to Allah desperately, calling upon Him in every position: lying down when too weak to rise, sitting, or standing. In their distress, they instinctively recognize that only Allah can help them. This innate recognition of Allah in hardship reveals the natural disposition (fitrah) within every human.",
    "But when We relieve their hardship, they return to their old ways as if they had never cried to Us to remove any hardship!": "Tragically, once Allah answers their desperate prayers and removes their suffering, many people quickly forget. They return to neglecting Allah, committing sins, and living as if they never needed Him. They walk away from the very One who saved them, showing shocking ingratitude.",
    "This is how the misdeeds of the transgressors have been made appealing to them.": "Those who exceed all limits (musrifeen—the extravagant in sin) find their sinful lifestyle attractive. Their bad deeds seem good to them; their ingratitude feels normal. This self-deception is part of their punishment—they cannot see the ugliness of their behavior because they have chosen to blind themselves to truth."
  },
  13: {
    "We surely destroyed ˹other˺ peoples before you when they did wrong,": "History is filled with nations that Allah destroyed because of their wrongdoing—the people of Noah, 'Ad, Thamud, the people of Lot, and Pharaoh's people. Their ruins remain as silent witnesses to Allah's punishment. These were not small groups but powerful civilizations brought to nothing.",
    "and their messengers came to them with clear proofs but they would not believe!": "These nations were not destroyed without warning. Each received a messenger with unmistakable evidence—miracles, clear arguments, and divine revelation. They rejected the truth despite its clarity. Their destruction came only after they were given every opportunity to believe.",
    "This is how We reward the wicked people.": "Destruction is the payment for persistent wickedness. Those who insist on rejecting truth and oppressing others will face consequences. This is not cruelty but justice—a natural outcome of their choices."
  },
  14: {
    "Then We made you their successors in the land": "After those destroyed nations, Allah established you (the present generation, including the Quraysh and all subsequent peoples) in the earth. You inherited land, resources, and opportunities that once belonged to others. You live where others used to live; you prosper where others were wiped out.",
    "to see how you would act.": "This succession is a test. Allah is watching how you will behave—will you learn from those who came before, or repeat their mistakes? Will you believe and do good, or disbelieve and transgress? The earth is your examination hall, and your actions are being recorded. The fate of previous nations should serve as a powerful warning."
  },
  15: {
    "When Our clear revelations are recited to them, those who do not expect to meet Us say ˹to the Prophet˺, \"Bring us a different Quran or make some changes in it.\"": "The disbelievers heard the Quran and understood its message clearly—too clearly for their comfort. It condemned their idols, their unjust practices, and their immoral behavior. So they asked for a different version: one that would allow them to keep their idols, or at least soften its criticism of their ways. This reveals that their rejection was not due to lack of understanding but due to unwillingness to change.",
    "Say ˹to them˺, \"It is not for me to change it on my own.": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to make clear that the Quran is not his personal composition that he can edit at will. He is a messenger, not the author. He has no authority to add, remove, or modify a single letter according to people's preferences.",
    "I only follow what is revealed to me.": "The Prophet's ﷺ role is to receive and convey. He follows divine revelation, not human wishes. This confirms the Quran's divine origin—it comes from Allah, and the Prophet faithfully transmits it without alteration.",
    "I fear, if I were to disobey my Lord, the punishment of a tremendous Day.\"": "Even the Prophet ﷺ—Allah's beloved messenger—declares his fear of disobeying Allah. If he were to alter the revelation (which he would never do), he would face punishment on the Day of Judgment. This emphasizes the seriousness of tampering with Allah's words and the Prophet's complete submission to his Lord."
  },
  16: {
    "Say, \"Had Allah willed, I would not have recited it to you, nor would He have made it known to you.": "The Quran's existence among them is by Allah's will alone. Allah chose to reveal it and chose Muhammad ﷺ to deliver it. This was entirely Allah's decision, demonstrating that the message is from Him, not invented by the Prophet.",
    "I had lived my whole life among you before this ˹revelation˺.": "The Prophet ﷺ lived among the Quraysh for forty years before prophethood. They knew him intimately—his character, his speech, his habits. He never composed poetry, never claimed special knowledge, never showed interest in religion beyond basic practices. Then suddenly, he brought this magnificent Quran. If it were his own invention, why did he wait forty years? Where did this sudden eloquence come from?",
    "Do you not understand?\"": "This rhetorical question challenges them to use their reason. If they thought honestly about the Prophet's ﷺ life before and after revelation, the conclusion would be obvious: this Quran cannot be his invention. It must be from a higher source. The appeal to reason is frequent in the Quran, showing that faith and intellect are partners, not enemies."
  },
  17: {
    "Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against Allah": "The greatest injustice is to attribute false statements to Allah—claiming He said what He did not say, or inventing religious practices without His authority. This includes those who accused the Prophet ﷺ of fabricating the Quran, thereby indirectly accusing Allah of allowing a liar to succeed in His name.",
    "or deny His revelations?": "Equally wrong is rejecting Allah's true revelations when they come. Both fabricating lies and denying truth are forms of supreme injustice against Allah, against truth, and against oneself.",
    "Indeed, the wicked will never succeed.": "Those who commit such crimes—inventing lies about Allah or rejecting His signs—will never achieve true success. They may have temporary worldly gains, but ultimate success in both worlds is forever denied to them. True success (falah) belongs only to those who believe and follow truth."
  },
  18: {
    "They worship besides Allah others who can neither harm nor benefit them,": "The idolaters worshipped beings—idols, angels, righteous dead people, or jinn—that had no power whatsoever. These objects of worship could not bring any benefit to their worshippers nor could they cause any harm. They were completely powerless, yet people devoted themselves to them.",
    "and say, \"These are our intercessors with Allah.\"": "Their justification was that these idols would intercede for them with Allah—bring them closer to Him, plead their case, and ensure divine favor. This was their rationale for idol worship: not that the idols were gods themselves, but that they served as intermediaries. This same flawed logic appears in various forms throughout history.",
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Are you informing Allah of something He does not know in the heavens or the earth?": "Allah challenges this belief with a devastating question: Are you telling Allah about partners and intercessors that He Himself is unaware of? If such intercessors existed with the power they claim, surely Allah—who knows everything in the heavens and earth—would know about them. The fact that Allah denies any such partners means they simply do not exist in the capacity the idolaters imagine.",
    "Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate ˹with Him˺!\"": "Allah is far above and free from the partners they ascribe to Him. He is complete, perfect, and self-sufficient. He needs no helpers, no intermediaries, and no partners. To associate anything with Him is to demean His majesty and insult His perfection."
  },
  19: {
    "Humanity was once nothing but a single community ˹of believers˺,": "In the beginning, humanity was united upon the natural belief in one God (fitrah). Whether referring to the time of Adam or the period before widespread idolatry, there was an era when people shared one faith and one way. This original unity was based on truth and monotheism.",
    "but then they differed.": "Over time, people diverged from this original path. Some innovated new beliefs, some followed their desires, and some were led astray by Satan. Thus emerged different religions, sects, and ideologies. This division was not part of Allah's original plan for humanity but resulted from human choices.",
    "Had it not been for a prior decree from your Lord,": "Allah had already decreed that judgment would be postponed to the Day of Judgment and that humans would be given time to make their choices. He decreed a term for this world to run its course before the final reckoning.",
    "their differences would have been settled ˹at once˺.": "If not for this divine decree of respite, Allah could have immediately judged between the differing factions, destroyed the wrongdoers, and vindicated the truthful. But His wisdom dictated giving humanity time—time to reflect, repent, and choose the right path before the final judgment."
  },
  20: {
    "They ask, \"Why has no ˹other˺ sign been sent down to him from his Lord?\"": "Despite the Quran being the greatest miracle, the disbelievers demanded additional signs—perhaps something like the staff of Moses or the miracles of Jesus. They wanted tangible, spectacular miracles as conditions for their belief. In reality, this was an excuse to avoid faith; had miracles come, they would have found other reasons to disbelieve.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"˹The knowledge of˺ the unseen is with Allah alone.": "The timing and nature of signs are Allah's decision alone. The Prophet ﷺ cannot produce miracles on demand; miracles come according to Allah's wisdom. Knowledge of when, how, and whether to send additional signs belongs exclusively to Allah.",
    "So wait! I too am waiting with you.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to tell them to wait—wait for Allah's judgment, wait to see who is right. This is not a threat but a statement of fact: time will reveal the truth. The Prophet waits with confidence in Allah's promise, while they wait in their denial, unaware of what awaits them."
  },
  21: {
    "When We give people a taste of mercy after being afflicted with a hardship,": "When relief comes after difficulty—recovery after illness, prosperity after poverty, safety after danger—people experience Allah's mercy. This shift should inspire gratitude and increased devotion.",
    "they swiftly devise plots against Our revelations!": "Instead of gratitude, some people immediately begin scheming against Allah's signs. They use their restored comfort to mock the revelation, persecute believers, or spread doubt about the truth. Their plotting shows that their hearts were never sincere; they only called upon Allah out of desperation, not devotion.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah is swifter in devising ˹punishment˺.": "Whatever schemes they make, Allah's plan is always ahead of theirs. They cannot outmaneuver the All-Knowing, All-Wise. Their plots will ultimately fail and backfire, while Allah's plan will succeed.",
    "Surely Our messenger-angels record whatever you devise.\"": "Every scheme, every whispered conspiracy, every secret plan is being recorded by the angels. Nothing is hidden from Allah. These records will be presented on the Day of Judgment as evidence. This should make every person think twice before plotting against the truth."
  },
  22: {
    "He is the One Who enables you to travel through land and sea.": "Allah facilitates all human travel. Whether journeying across deserts, mountains, and plains, or sailing across vast oceans, it is Allah who makes it possible. He created the means of transportation, the winds that propel ships, the animals that carry loads, and the intellect that designs vehicles.",
    "And it so happens that you are on ships, sailing with a favourable wind, to the passengers' delight.": "Picture a voyage going perfectly: the wind is cooperative, the sea is calm, and the passengers are relaxed and happy. They enjoy the journey, perhaps feeling self-sufficient and secure. Life is good, and they have no immediate worries.",
    "Suddenly, the ships are overcome by a gale wind and those on board are overwhelmed by waves from every side,": "In an instant, everything changes. A violent storm strikes—winds howl, waves tower from every direction, and the ship tosses helplessly. Technology and human skill suddenly seem useless against nature's fury. The passengers realize how fragile their situation truly is.",
    "and they assume they are doomed.": "Surrounded by danger with no human rescue possible, they conclude that death is imminent. In this moment of absolute helplessness, all illusions of self-sufficiency vanish. They see themselves as they truly are: utterly dependent on a higher power.",
    "They cry out to Allah ˹alone˺ in sincere devotion,": "In this desperate moment, they turn to Allah alone—not to idols, not to saints, not to anyone else. Their supplication is pure, devoid of any partners. This sincerity emerges because when death stares them in the face, their hearts instinctively recognize that only Allah can save them.",
    "\"If You save us from this, we will certainly be grateful.\"": "They make promises to Allah: if He rescues them, they will reform, they will be grateful, they will worship Him properly. In their terror, they vow to change their ways. These promises flow easily when life hangs by a thread."
  },
  23: {
    "But as soon as He rescues them, they transgress in the land unjustly.": "The moment they reach safety, their promises evaporate. They return to their old ways—sinning, oppressing others, and forgetting Allah. The gratitude they swore lasts only as long as the danger. This pattern reveals the worst of human nature: using Allah in emergencies but ignoring Him in prosperity.",
    "O humanity! Your transgression is only against your own souls.": "Allah addresses all people directly: when you sin and rebel, you harm no one but yourselves. Allah is not diminished by your disobedience; His kingdom is not threatened. But your souls are damaged, your afterlife is ruined, and you accumulate punishment for yourself.",
    "˹There is only˺ brief enjoyment in this worldly life,": "Whatever pleasure you gain from transgression is temporary. This world, with all its attractions, is fleeting. The enjoyment of sin is momentary, but its consequences are lasting. The whole lifespan of this world compared to eternity is like a drop compared to an ocean.",
    "then to Us is your return, and then We will inform you of what you used to do.": "After this brief worldly life, everyone returns to Allah. No one escapes this appointment. Then Allah will reveal to each person exactly what they did—every transgression, every broken promise, every moment of ingratitude. Nothing will be hidden or forgotten."
  },
  24: {
    "The life of this world is just like rain We send down from the sky,": "Allah presents a powerful parable. Just as rain descends from above—a blessing that brings life—worldly pleasures seem to promise happiness and fulfillment. Everything appears to be going well.",
    "producing a mixture of plants which humans and animals consume.": "The rain causes vegetation to sprout—crops for humans, pastures for animals. The earth becomes green and productive. Likewise, worldly life produces things people enjoy: wealth, health, relationships, achievements. Everything seems abundant and promising.",
    "Then just as the earth looks its best, perfectly beautified,": "The earth reaches its peak of beauty—lush, green, covered with flowers and crops. It is a stunning sight. Similarly, worldly life sometimes reaches moments of perfection: everything is going well, health is good, wealth is abundant, and happiness seems complete.",
    "and its people think they have full control over it,": "At this peak, people begin to feel secure. They believe they have mastered their circumstances—their wealth is safe, their health is stable, their future is planned. They feel in control, as if nothing can go wrong.",
    "there comes to it Our command by night or by day,": "Suddenly, unexpectedly, Allah's command comes. It could strike at any moment—in the darkness of night or the brightness of day. A storm, a frost, a disease, a disaster—something beyond human control intervenes.",
    "so We mow it down as if it never flourished yesterday!": "In an instant, the beautiful earth becomes barren stubble, as if it had never been green. All that beauty, all that abundance, gone in a moment. The same happens to worldly life: health fails, wealth disappears, relationships end, and death arrives. What seemed permanent was always temporary.",
    "This is how We make the signs clear for people who reflect.": "This parable is for those who think deeply. Surface-level thinking misses the point. But those who reflect will see the obvious lesson: this world is not the goal. It is beautiful but temporary, promising but fleeting. The wise person invests in what lasts—the Hereafter."
  },
  25: {
    "And Allah invites ˹all˺ to the Home of Peace": "While this world is temporary and uncertain, Allah offers something better: the Home of Peace (Dar as-Salam)—Paradise. It is called the Home of Peace because it is free from all troubles, fears, sorrows, and conflicts. Allah Himself invites humanity to this eternal abode. The invitation is open to everyone, but not everyone accepts.",
    "and guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path.": "Allah guides to Paradise those whom He chooses—and He chooses those who sincerely seek guidance and make effort toward it. This guidance is to the straight path, the direct route to success. Allah does not force anyone, but He facilitates guidance for those who genuinely want it."
  },
  26: {
    "Those who do good will have the finest reward": "People who excel in faith and righteous deeds will receive the best reward—Paradise with all its pleasures: gardens, rivers, pure spouses, eternal youth, and freedom from all pain and sadness. Their reward matches and exceeds their efforts.",
    "and ˹even˺ more.": "Beyond Paradise itself, they receive something even greater—the vision of Allah's Face. The Prophet ﷺ explained that this 'more' (ziyadah) refers to looking at Allah, the greatest joy a believer can experience. This is the ultimate reward, surpassing all other pleasures.",
    "Neither gloom nor disgrace will cover their faces.": "Their faces will never be touched by sadness, darkness, or humiliation. In this world, hardship and worry leave marks on faces. In Paradise, believers will be radiant, joyful, and dignified forever. No fear, no regret, no shame.",
    "It is they who will be the residents of Paradise. They will be there forever.": "These blessed souls will dwell in Paradise eternally—not as visitors but as permanent residents. Their stay has no end, their joy has no decline, and their blessings have no limit. Forever is their reward for choosing truth over falsehood."
  },
  27: {
    "As for those who commit evil, the reward of an evil deed is its equivalent.": "Those who chose evil will be repaid with punishment equal to their crimes—no more, no less. Allah is perfectly just; He does not punish beyond what is deserved. Every evil deed has its proportionate consequence.",
    "Humiliation will cover them—": "Disgrace and shame will envelop them completely. The arrogance they showed in this world, rejecting truth and mocking believers, will be replaced by utter humiliation. Their pride will become their downfall.",
    "with no one to protect them from Allah—": "On that Day, they will find no defender, no helper, no advocate. The false gods they worshipped, the powerful connections they relied upon, the wealth they accumulated—none of it will shield them from Allah's judgment.",
    "as if their faces were covered with patches of the night's deep darkness.": "Their faces will be darkened with gloom—as if pieces of the darkest night were plastered onto them. This imagery contrasts sharply with the radiant faces of believers. Their outward darkness reflects their inward spiritual state: lives spent in the darkness of disbelief.",
    "It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever.": "Just as the believers are permanent residents of Paradise, the disbelievers are permanent residents of Hell. Their stay is eternal—not temporary punishment but an everlasting consequence of their rejection of truth. This is the ultimate failure: eternal loss of Allah's mercy and eternal residence in the Fire."
  },
  28: {
    "˹Consider˺ the Day We will gather them all together": "On the Day of Judgment, every human being from the first to the last will be assembled before Allah. No one will be absent—not the powerful nor the weak, not the ancient nor the modern. This gathering is certain and comprehensive.",
    "then say to those who associated others ˹with Allah in worship˺, \"Stay in your places—you and your associate-gods.\"": "The polytheists will be commanded to remain where they are along with whatever they used to worship besides Allah—whether idols, angels, jinn, or righteous people they elevated to divine status. This is a moment of confrontation and exposure.",
    "We will separate them from each other,": "Allah will separate the worshippers from those they worshipped. The false bond they imagined between themselves and their 'gods' will be severed. The relationship they thought would benefit them will be torn apart in front of everyone.",
    "and their associate-gods will say, \"It was not us that you worshipped!\"": "The objects of their worship will deny any connection to them. The idols, angels, or righteous people they invoked will disown them completely. They will declare that they never asked to be worshipped and had no knowledge of this worship. This is the ultimate betrayal—the 'gods' they devoted their lives to will abandon them when they need them most."
  },
  29: {
    "Allah is sufficient as a Witness between each of us": "Those who were falsely worshipped will call upon Allah to testify to the truth. Allah, who sees and knows everything, will confirm their innocence. His testimony is the ultimate proof that cannot be challenged or denied.",
    "that we were totally unaware of your worship.\"": "The false gods will declare complete ignorance of being worshipped. The idols were lifeless and senseless; the angels and righteous people never knew they were being invoked. This ignorance proves that the worship was entirely misdirected and utterly useless. The polytheists worshipped beings who neither knew nor cared about their devotion."
  },
  30: {
    "Then and there every soul will face ˹the consequences of˺ what it had done.": "At that moment, each person will be confronted with their complete record of deeds. Nothing will be hidden or forgotten. Every action—good or bad—will be presented, and each soul will taste the results of its choices.",
    "They all will be returned to Allah—their True Master.": "Everyone will be brought back to Allah, who is the only true Lord and Master. The false masters they followed in this world—whether idols, desires, or tyrants—will have no authority on that Day. Only Allah's lordship is real; all others were illusions.",
    "And whatever ˹gods˺ they fabricated will fail them.": "Everything they invented and associated with Allah will vanish and prove worthless. Their fabricated deities will offer no help, no intercession, and no protection. All their religious innovations and false beliefs will disappear like mirages, leaving them with nothing but their sins."
  },
  31: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Who provides for you from heaven and earth?": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to pose a direct question: Who sends down rain from the sky and causes crops to grow from the earth? Who ensures your sustenance—food, water, and all life's necessities? The answer is obvious, and even the polytheists knew it.",
    "Who owns ˹your˺ hearing and sight?": "Who created your ears and eyes and maintains their function? These faculties are not self-created. Someone gave them to you and keeps them working. Can your idols grant hearing to the deaf or sight to the blind?",
    "Who brings forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living?": "Who produces a living creature from a lifeless seed, or a vibrant plant from dead soil? Who causes living beings to die and returns them to the earth? This cycle of life and death is under someone's control—whose?",
    "And who conducts every affair?\"": "Who manages the affairs of the entire universe—the movement of celestial bodies, the changing of seasons, the balance of ecosystems, and the countless processes that sustain existence? This administration requires infinite knowledge and power.",
    "They will ˹surely˺ say, \"Allah.\"": "Even the polytheists of Makkah, when confronted with these questions, would admit that only Allah does all these things. Their idols clearly had no such powers. This admission was extracted from their own mouths.",
    "Say, \"Will you not then fear ˹Him˺?": "If you acknowledge that Allah alone does all this, why do you not fear Him alone? Why do you not worship Him exclusively? Your acknowledgment of His lordship should logically lead to His exclusive worship. Fear Allah and abandon partners that have no power whatsoever."
  },
  32: {
    "That is Allah—your True Lord.": "This Allah—the one you admit provides, owns, brings life and death, and manages all affairs—is your real Lord. There is no other true lord besides Him. All other claims to divinity are false.",
    "So what is beyond the truth except falsehood?": "This is a logical principle: once you have truth, anything else is falsehood. There is no middle ground between truth and error. If Allah is the true Lord, then anything worshipped besides Him is necessarily false. There are only two options: truth or misguidance.",
    "How can you then be turned away?\"": "Given this clear reasoning, how can you be diverted from the truth? What could possibly lead you away from worshipping the One you yourselves acknowledge as the only true Lord? This question exposes the irrationality of polytheism."
  },
  33: {
    "And so your Lord's decree has been proven true against the rebellious—": "Allah's word and decree stands fulfilled regarding those who persist in rebellion. When people insist on rejecting truth despite clear evidence, Allah's promise concerning them takes effect. They have earned their fate through their own choices.",
    "that they will never believe.": "Due to their persistent rebellion and rejection, they have reached a point where they will never believe. This is not Allah forcing them to disbelieve; rather, their stubborn choices have sealed their hearts. They chose disbelief so consistently that belief became impossible for them—a consequence of their own making."
  },
  34: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Can any of your associate-gods originate creation and then resurrect it?\"": "Pose another challenge: Can any of the beings you worship create anything from nothing? Can they bring something into existence, and then after it dies, bring it back to life? This is the test of true divinity—the power to create and resurrect.",
    "Say, \"˹Only˺ Allah originates creation and then resurrects it.": "When they cannot answer, provide the truth: Only Allah creates initially and only He can recreate after death. This power belongs to no one else. The idols never created a fly, let alone a human being, and certainly cannot resurrect anything.",
    "How can you then be deluded ˹from the truth˺?\"": "Given this undeniable reality, how can you be so deceived? What delusion has captured your minds that you worship powerless beings while acknowledging that only Allah has the power to create? This question strikes at the irrationality of their beliefs."
  },
  35: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Can any of your associate-gods guide to the truth?\"": "Here is another test: Can your idols guide anyone to truth, to righteousness, to salvation? Can they reveal what is right and wrong, show the path to Paradise, or save anyone from error?",
    "Say, \"˹Only˺ Allah guides to the truth.\"": "The answer is clear: Only Allah provides true guidance. He sent prophets, revealed scriptures, and clarified the path to success. No idol ever communicated truth to anyone or guided a single soul.",
    "Who then is more worthy to be followed: the One Who guides to the truth or those who cannot find the way unless guided?": "A profound comparison: On one side is Allah, who guides others to truth. On the other side are beings that cannot even guide themselves—they need guidance like everyone else. Which one deserves to be followed? The answer is obvious to anyone with basic reasoning.",
    "What is the matter with you? How do you judge?\"": "This rhetorical question expresses astonishment at their flawed judgment. How can rational beings choose to follow powerless, guideless entities over the All-Powerful, All-Guiding Lord? Their judgment is completely backwards."
  },
  36: {
    "Most of them follow nothing but ˹inherited˺ assumptions.": "The majority of polytheists do not base their beliefs on evidence or revelation. They simply follow what they inherited from their ancestors—assumptions, guesswork, and traditions passed down without verification. They worship idols because their fathers did, not because they have any proof.",
    "˹And˺ surely assumptions can in no way replace the truth.": "Conjecture and guesswork cannot substitute for certainty and truth. In matters of religion and the afterlife, assumptions are worthless. You cannot build your eternal fate on mere speculation. Truth comes from Allah through revelation, not from human guesses.",
    "Allah is indeed All-Knowing of what they do.": "Allah knows everything they do—their false assumptions, their blind following, their stubborn rejection of truth. Nothing escapes His knowledge. This is both a warning and a reminder that accountability is coming."
  },
  37: {
    "It is not ˹possible˺ for this Quran to have been produced by anyone other than Allah.": "The Quran cannot possibly be a human fabrication. Its eloquence, its consistency, its knowledge of the unseen, its prophetic accuracy, its impact on hearts—all point to a divine origin. No human, including the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ who was unlettered, could produce such a book.",
    "In fact, it is a confirmation of what came before,": "The Quran confirms the essential truths of previous scriptures—the Torah, the Psalms, the Gospel. It affirms monotheism, prophethood, the afterlife, and moral principles found in earlier revelations. This continuity proves its divine source; Allah sent all scriptures.",
    "and an explanation of the Scripture.": "The Quran clarifies, explains, and expands upon what was revealed before. It corrects distortions that crept into earlier scriptures and provides detailed guidance for all aspects of life. It is the final, comprehensive revelation.",
    "It is, without a doubt, from the Lord of all worlds.": "There is absolutely no doubt about the Quran's origin—it comes from the Lord of all creation. This certainty is emphasized because the stakes are so high. The Quran is not a matter of opinion but established truth from the Creator of everything."
  },
  38: {
    "Or do they claim, \"He made it up!\"?": "The disbelievers accused the Prophet ﷺ of inventing the Quran himself. This accusation contradicts their own knowledge of him as an unlettered man with no training in poetry or religious scholarship.",
    "Tell them ˹O Prophet˺, \"Produce one sûrah like it then,": "If the Quran is man-made, then producing something similar should be possible. The challenge is issued: create just one chapter (surah) that matches the Quran's eloquence, depth, and impact. Some surahs are only a few lines long, making this challenge seemingly easy—yet no one has ever succeeded.",
    "and seek help from whoever you can—other than Allah—if what you say is true!\"": "They are permitted to gather all their poets, scholars, and experts. They can call upon their idols, jinn, or anyone else for assistance. With all resources combined, let them produce a single surah like the Quran. This challenge has stood for over 1400 years, unanswered."
  },
  39: {
    "In fact, they ˹hastily˺ rejected the Book without comprehending it": "Their rejection was premature and ignorant. They denied the Quran without taking time to understand it, without pondering its meanings, and without giving it fair consideration. Their rejection was based on arrogance and bias, not on careful examination.",
    "and before the fulfilment of its warnings.": "They rejected it before seeing its prophecies come true and before experiencing the warnings it contains. When those warnings materialize—whether in this world or the next—they will realize their mistake, but it will be too late.",
    "Similarly, those before them were in denial.": "This pattern of hasty rejection is not new. Previous nations also denied their messengers and scriptures without proper consideration. The Quraysh were repeating history.",
    "See then what was the end of the wrongdoers!": "Look at what happened to those previous nations—destroyed, ruined, their civilizations reduced to rubble. Their ruins serve as warnings to anyone paying attention. The same fate awaits all who follow their path of denial."
  },
  40: {
    "Some of them will ˹eventually˺ believe in it; others will not.": "Among the people hearing the Quran, there will be different responses. Some hearts will open to the truth and embrace faith; others will remain sealed in rejection. This diversity is expected—people have free will and make different choices.",
    "And your Lord knows best the corruptors.": "Allah knows exactly who the corruptors are—those who spread falsehood, mislead others, and actively oppose the truth. He knows their intentions, their plotting, and their ultimate fate. Nothing is hidden from Him, and He will deal with them accordingly."
  },
  41: {
    "If they deny you, then say, \"My deeds are mine and your deeds are yours.": "If they persist in rejection despite all evidence, make a clear separation. You are responsible for your actions, and they are responsible for theirs. Each person will bear the consequences of their own choices.",
    "You are free of what I do and I am free of what you do!\"": "This statement establishes complete separation of accountability. They will not be blamed for the Prophet's actions, nor will he bear responsibility for theirs. On the Day of Judgment, each person stands alone with their record. This is also a warning: they cannot expect any help from the Prophet if they choose to reject him."
  },
  42: {
    "Some of them listen to what you say,": "Some disbelievers appear to listen to the Prophet's recitation of the Quran. They hear the words with their ears, attending to the sounds.",
    "but can you make the deaf hear even though they do not understand?": "Though they technically hear, they are spiritually deaf. Their hearts are closed, so the message does not penetrate. The Prophet ﷺ cannot force understanding upon those who refuse to comprehend. True hearing requires an open heart, not just functioning ears. This consoles the Prophet: the failure to believe is not his fault but theirs."
  },
  43: {
    "And some of them look at you,": "Some disbelievers look at the Prophet ﷺ—they see him, observe his character, witness his miracles, and notice the signs of his prophethood.",
    "but can you guide the blind even though they cannot see?": "Despite having functioning eyes, they are spiritually blind. They see evidence but cannot perceive truth. The Prophet ﷺ cannot force sight upon those determined to remain blind. Guidance requires willingness to see, and they have chosen blindness. Again, this is consolation: the Prophet has fulfilled his duty; their blindness is their own doing."
  },
  44: {
    "Indeed, Allah does not wrong people in the least,": "Allah is perfectly just. He never wrongs anyone even in the smallest matter—not an atom's weight of injustice comes from Him. Every punishment is deserved, every reward is earned, and every decree is fair.",
    "but it is people who wrong themselves.": "When people suffer bad consequences, it is due to their own choices. They wrong themselves by rejecting truth, committing sins, and turning away from guidance. Allah provides guidance, evidence, and opportunity; people choose to reject and harm themselves. The blame lies entirely with the individual, not with Allah."
  },
  45: {
    "On the Day He will gather them, it will be as if they had not stayed ˹in the world˺ except for an hour of a day,": "When people are resurrected and gathered, their entire worldly life—decades or even a century—will seem like it lasted only an hour. The long years will compress into a brief moment in their memory. This perception reveals how insignificant worldly life is compared to eternity.",
    "˹as though they were only˺ getting to know one another.": "Their time on earth will seem so short that it's as if they barely had time to meet and recognize each other. All their worldly achievements, possessions, and concerns will seem trivial. What felt so important will appear fleeting.",
    "Lost indeed will be those who denied the meeting with Allah,": "Those who denied resurrection and the Day of Judgment will realize their catastrophic mistake. Their denial did not prevent the Day from coming—it only prevented them from preparing. Now they face the consequences unprepared.",
    "and were not ˹rightly˺ guided!": "They were not guided because they refused guidance. The truth was offered to them, but they rejected it. Now, facing the reality they denied, they see their eternal loss clearly."
  },
  46: {
    "Whether We show you ˹O Prophet˺ some of what We threaten them with,": "Allah may allow the Prophet ﷺ to witness some of the punishment promised to the disbelievers—such as defeat in battle or other hardships—during his lifetime.",
    "or cause you to die ˹before that˺,": "Or the Prophet ﷺ may pass away before seeing these punishments unfold. Either way, the outcome is certain; only the timing varies.",
    "to Us is their return": "Regardless of when or how punishment comes, all disbelievers will ultimately return to Allah. Whether they face consequences in this world or not, the meeting with Allah is guaranteed.",
    "and Allah is a Witness over what they do.": "Allah observes everything they do—every plot, every rejection, every sin. His witness is complete and infallible. Nothing escapes His knowledge, and everything will be presented on the Day of Judgment."
  },
  47: {
    "And for every community there is a messenger.": "Allah's justice is complete: no nation has been left without guidance. Every community throughout history received a messenger to convey the truth. This ensures that no one can claim ignorance on the Day of Judgment.",
    "After their messenger has come, judgment is passed on them in all fairness,": "Once a messenger delivers the message and establishes proof, judgment follows. Those who accepted are rewarded; those who rejected face consequences. This judgment is perfectly fair—based on clear evidence presented to them.",
    "and they are not wronged.": "No one receives unjust treatment. The punishment matches the crime, and mercy is given where deserved. Allah's system ensures complete equity—no favoritism, no excessive punishment, no overlooked good deed."
  },
  48: {
    "They ask ˹the believers˺, \"When will this threat come to pass if what you say is true?\"": "The disbelievers mockingly demand to know exactly when the promised punishment will arrive. This question reflects their disbelief and arrogance. They assume that since punishment hasn't come immediately, it never will. They challenge the believers to specify a date, thinking this will expose them as false."
  },
  49: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"I have no power to benefit or protect myself, except by the Will of Allah.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to clarify his role: he is a human messenger, not a controller of fate. He cannot bring harm or benefit to himself without Allah's permission, let alone control the timing of divine punishment. This honest declaration distinguishes him from false prophets who make grandiose claims.",
    "For each community there is an appointed term.": "Every nation has a predetermined lifespan—a deadline set by Allah. When that term approaches, the community faces its fate. This timing is Allah's decision alone.",
    "When their time arrives, they cannot delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it.": "Once Allah's decree is due, nothing can postpone it—not by a second. Nor can it come before its appointed time. The timing is precisely fixed. This should instill both fear and urgency: no one knows when their time is up."
  },
  50: {
    "Tell them ˹O Prophet˺, \"Imagine if His torment were to overcome you by night or day—": "Ask them to truly contemplate: what if Allah's punishment suddenly descended upon you while you slept at night or went about your day? You would have no warning, no preparation, no escape.",
    "do the wicked realize what they are ˹really˺ asking Him to hasten?": "Do the criminals understand what they're demanding? They mockingly ask for punishment to come quickly, as if it were a joke. But if they truly understood the severity of divine wrath, they would tremble at the thought and beg for delay, not haste. Their mockery reveals their ignorance."
  },
  51: {
    "Will you believe in it only after it has overtaken you?": "When punishment actually strikes, suddenly they will believe. But of what use is faith at that moment? The time for faith is before punishment, not during it. Faith under duress, when no other option remains, is not accepted.",
    "Now? But you always wanted to hasten it!\"": "At that moment, they will be told: 'Now you believe? After all your mockery, after demanding it be hastened, after all your arrogance?' This rhetorical question exposes their foolishness. They asked for it, and now it has come—too late for belief to save them."
  },
  52: {
    "Then the wrongdoers will be told, \"Taste the torment of eternity!": "They will be addressed directly: experience now the eternal punishment. The word 'taste' suggests an experiential suffering—not just observing but feeling the torment. 'Eternity' removes any hope of escape or end.",
    "Are you not rewarded except for what you used to commit?\"": "This punishment is not arbitrary or unjust. It is precisely what they earned through their deeds. They chose disbelief, mockery, and sin; now they receive the appropriate payment. No one can claim unfair treatment."
  },
  53: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺, \"Is this true?\"": "The disbelievers ask whether the resurrection, judgment, and punishment are real. Despite their mockery, a part of them wants to know the truth. Or perhaps they ask sarcastically, expecting denial.",
    "Say, \"Yes, by my Lord! Most certainly it is true!": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to give the most emphatic affirmation possible—swearing by Allah Himself. Yes, resurrection is true. Judgment is true. Paradise and Hell are true. There is no room for doubt.",
    "And you will have no escape.\"": "Once Allah's decree comes, no one can escape it. There will be no hiding place, no defense, no exit. The certainty of this truth should motivate immediate preparation through faith and good deeds."
  },
  54: {
    "If every wrongdoer were to possess everything in the world, they would surely ransom themselves with it.": "If a single sinner owned all the wealth on earth—every piece of gold, every property, every treasure—they would gladly give it all to escape punishment. But no ransom will be accepted. The time for earning salvation through deeds has passed; no amount of wealth can buy freedom from Hell.",
    "They will hide ˹their˺ remorse when they see the torment.": "When they witness the punishment, overwhelming regret will fill them. They will try to conceal their remorse—perhaps from pride or shame—but it will consume them internally. The regret of that Day will be unlike any worldly regret.",
    "And they will be judged in all fairness,": "Despite their suffering, the judgment will be perfectly just. Every punishment will match the crime precisely. Allah's justice is flawless.",
    "and none will be wronged.": "No excess punishment, no unfair treatment. Even in Hell, justice prevails. This emphasizes that their fate is entirely self-earned through their choices."
  },
  55: {
    "Surely to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth.": "Allah owns everything—every atom in the universe belongs to Him. This ownership is total and unchallenged. He created it all, sustains it all, and controls it all. Nothing exists outside His dominion.",
    "Surely Allah's promise is ˹always˺ true,": "Every promise Allah makes will be fulfilled. His promise of resurrection, judgment, reward, and punishment is absolutely certain. Unlike human promises that may fail, Allah's word never fails.",
    "but most of them do not know.": "Despite the clear evidence, most people remain ignorant of this truth. They do not know—or refuse to know—that Allah's promise is certain. This ignorance leads them to live as if there is no accountability, to their ultimate loss."
  },
  56: {
    "He ˹is the One Who˺ gives life and causes death,": "Allah alone grants life and takes it away. Every birth is by His will; every death is by His decree. No one else has this power. This control over the most fundamental aspects of existence proves His absolute sovereignty.",
    "and to Him you will ˹all˺ be returned.": "After death, every soul returns to Allah. There is no alternative destination, no escape route, no other judge. This return is the ultimate reality that should shape how we live. Everything we do moves us toward this inevitable meeting with our Creator."
  },
  57: {
    "O humanity! Indeed, there has come to you a warning from your Lord,": "Allah addresses all of humanity—not just Arabs, not just one era, but every human being. What has come is a profound admonition from the Lord of all creation. This warning alerts people to the consequences of disbelief and sin, urging them to wake up before it's too late.",
    "a cure for what is in the hearts,": "The Quran heals spiritual diseases—doubt, hypocrisy, envy, arrogance, hatred, and all ailments of the heart. Just as medicine cures physical illness, the Quran cures the soul. When hearts are sick with sin and doubt, the Quran provides the remedy. This healing is available to anyone who sincerely engages with it.",
    "a guide,": "The Quran shows the straight path—the way to success in this life and the next. In a world full of confusion and competing ideologies, the Quran provides clear direction. It distinguishes truth from falsehood, right from wrong, beneficial from harmful.",
    "and a mercy for the believers.": "For those who believe, the Quran is a special mercy. It brings them peace, purpose, and the promise of Paradise. While the Quran offers guidance to all, its full mercy is realized by those who accept and follow it. Believers experience the Quran's mercy in their daily lives—comfort in hardship, guidance in confusion, and hope in despair."
  },
  58: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"In Allah's grace and mercy let them rejoice.": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to announce what truly deserves celebration. Allah's grace (the Quran, Islam, guidance) and His mercy (forgiveness, Paradise, blessings) are the real causes for joy. These are the greatest gifts a person can receive.",
    "That is far better than whatever ˹wealth˺ they amass.\"": "All the gold, property, and worldly treasures people accumulate cannot compare to Allah's guidance and mercy. Wealth is temporary—it can be lost, stolen, or left behind at death. But Allah's grace and mercy lead to eternal bliss. The wise person rejoices more in faith than in fortune."
  },
  59: {
    "Ask ˹the pagans, O Prophet˺, \"Have you seen that which Allah has sent down for you as a provision,": "Allah challenges the pagans about their religious practices. He provided sustenance—food, drink, livestock—for humanity's benefit. These provisions came from Allah, the true Lawgiver.",
    "of which you have made some lawful and some unlawful?\"": "The pagans invented their own religious rules, declaring certain foods or animals forbidden without any authority from Allah. They prohibited things Allah had permitted and permitted things Allah had forbidden—all based on their own whims and ancestral traditions.",
    "Say, \"Has Allah given you authorization,": "Did Allah actually command these prohibitions? Do you have any revelation, any proof, any divine sanction for these invented rules? The answer is clearly no.",
    "or are you fabricating lies against Allah?\"": "If Allah did not authorize these laws, then declaring them in His name is lying about Allah—one of the gravest sins. Making up religious rules and attributing them to Allah is a serious offense, yet they did it casually. This verse warns against innovating in religion without divine authority."
  },
  60: {
    "What do those who fabricate lies against Allah expect on Judgment Day?": "Have they considered the consequences? Those who invent religious falsehoods and attribute them to Allah—what do they think will happen when they stand before Him? This rhetorical question forces them to contemplate their fate. The Day of Judgment will expose every lie.",
    "Surely Allah is ever Bountiful to humanity,": "Despite their lies and ingratitude, Allah continues to shower humanity with blessings. He provides sustenance, health, guidance, and countless favors. His generosity is constant and abundant, extending even to those who disobey Him.",
    "but most of them are ungrateful.": "Despite receiving Allah's endless bounties, most people fail to thank Him properly. They take blessings for granted, attribute them to their own efforts, or use them in disobedience. Gratitude is rare, and this ingratitude is one of humanity's greatest failures."
  },
  61: {
    "There is no activity you may be engaged in ˹O Prophet˺ or portion of the Quran you may be reciting,": "Allah begins by addressing the Prophet ﷺ directly: whatever state you are in, whatever verse of the Quran you are reciting—Allah is fully aware. The Prophet's every moment is under divine observation.",
    "nor any deed you ˹all˺ may be doing except that We are a Witness over you while doing it.": "This extends to all people—every action anyone performs, Allah witnesses it in real time. Not a single deed escapes His observation. Whether in public or private, in darkness or light, alone or in a crowd—Allah sees everything as it happens.",
    "Not ˹even˺ an atom's weight is hidden from your Lord on earth or in heaven;": "Allah's knowledge extends to the smallest particles. An atom's weight—something invisible to the human eye—is completely known to Allah. Nothing on earth or in the vast heavens escapes His awareness.",
    "nor anything smaller or larger than that, but is ˹written˺ in a perfect Record.": "Whether smaller than an atom or larger than galaxies, everything is recorded in a clear, comprehensive book (Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz, the Preserved Tablet). This record is perfect—nothing is missing, nothing is incorrect. This should inspire awe and motivate careful living, knowing every action is permanently documented."
  },
  62: {
    "There will certainly be no fear for the close servants of Allah,": "Allah's awliya (close friends, devoted servants) have a special promise: they will experience no fear. This includes freedom from fear of the future—the Day of Judgment, punishment, or any coming hardship. Allah protects them from the terror that overwhelms others.",
    "nor will they grieve.": "They will also be free from grief over the past—no sorrow over missed opportunities, lost loved ones, or worldly failures. While others drown in regret, the awliya experience peace. This promise applies both in this world (through contentment) and in the Hereafter (through eternal bliss)."
  },
  63: {
    "˹They are˺ those who are faithful": "Who are these blessed awliya? First, they are people of genuine faith—they believe in Allah, His messengers, His books, the Day of Judgment, and all that faith requires. Their belief is sincere, not superficial.",
    "and are mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Second, they have taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads them to obey His commands and avoid His prohibitions. They live with awareness that Allah is watching, and this awareness shapes their choices. Faith and taqwa together define Allah's close servants. These qualities are attainable by anyone—the door to becoming Allah's wali is open to all."
  },
  64: {
    "For them is good news in this worldly life and the Hereafter.": "Allah's close servants receive glad tidings in both worlds. In this life, they may receive good news through righteous dreams, the love people have for them, praise at death, or inner peace and contentment. In the Hereafter, they receive the ultimate good news: admission to Paradise and Allah's pleasure.",
    "There is no change in the promise of Allah.": "What Allah promises, He delivers. His words never change; His commitments never fail. The good news promised to the believers is guaranteed—no force can alter Allah's decree. This provides absolute certainty and security for the faithful.",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the ultimate triumph.": "This is the greatest success possible—freedom from fear and grief, good news in both worlds, and Allah's unchanging promise. No worldly achievement compares to this triumph. Those who attain Allah's friendship have won everything that truly matters."
  },
  65: {
    "Do not let their words grieve you ˹O Prophet˺.": "The Prophet ﷺ is consoled: do not be saddened by the insults, mockery, and threats of the disbelievers. Their words may hurt, but they cannot harm Allah's cause. The Prophet is a human with feelings, and Allah acknowledges his pain while offering comfort.",
    "Surely all honour and power belongs to Allah.": "All 'izzah (honor, might, power) belongs exclusively to Allah. The disbelievers may seem powerful, but their power is borrowed and temporary. True, lasting power is with Allah alone. He will honor His messenger and humiliate the arrogant rejectors.",
    "He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears every word they say—every insult, every plot, every whisper. He knows their intentions and plans. Nothing escapes Him. This is both a comfort to the Prophet (Allah will handle them) and a warning to the disbelievers (Allah knows exactly what you're doing)."
  },
  66: {
    "Certainly to Allah ˹alone˺ belong all those in the heavens and all those on the earth.": "Every being in existence—angels in the heavens, humans and jinn on earth, and everything else—belongs to Allah. He owns everything and everyone. Nothing has independent existence outside His dominion.",
    "And what do those who associate others with Allah really follow?": "When polytheists worship other beings besides Allah, what are they actually following? What is the reality behind their devotion to idols, saints, or other deities?",
    "They follow nothing but assumptions and do nothing but lie.": "Their entire religious system is built on guesswork and falsehood. They have no revelation, no proof, no solid evidence. They assume their idols have power; they assume their ancestors were right; they assume intercession will work. It's all conjecture and lies, not truth."
  },
  67: {
    "He is the One Who has made the night for you to rest in": "Allah designed the night for rest and sleep. The darkness, the quiet, the coolness—all facilitate recovery from the day's exertions. This is a mercy and a sign of Allah's care for His creation.",
    "and the day bright.": "The day is made bright with sunlight, enabling work, travel, and productivity. Light allows people to see, earn their livelihood, and accomplish their tasks. This alternation between rest and activity is perfectly suited to human needs.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who listen.": "Those who truly listen—not just with their ears but with their hearts—will recognize these signs. The daily cycle of night and day, experienced by everyone, points clearly to a wise, caring Creator. But only attentive listeners perceive the message behind the routine."
  },
  68: {
    "They say, \"Allah has offspring.\"": "Some claimed that angels were Allah's daughters (the Arab pagans), others claimed Jesus was God's son (some Christians), and others made similar claims. This verse addresses all who attribute children to Allah.",
    "Glory be to Him!": "Allah is far above such claims! This expression (Subhanahu) declares Allah's perfection and freedom from any deficiency or inappropriate attribute. Having children implies need, physical processes, and similarity to creation—all of which are beneath Allah's majesty.",
    "He is the Self-Sufficient.": "Allah is Al-Ghani—completely independent, needing nothing and no one. Humans have children for companionship, help, or continuation of lineage. Allah needs none of this. He is eternally self-sufficient, so why would He need offspring?",
    "To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth.": "Everything already belongs to Allah—why would He need to \"have\" a child when He owns all creation? Angels, humans, animals, and all beings are His servants and property, not His children in any literal sense.",
    "You have no proof of this!": "Those making this claim have zero evidence. No revelation supports it; no reason demands it. It is a baseless assertion invented by human imagination.",
    "Do you say about Allah what you do not know?": "This rhetorical question condemns speaking about Allah without knowledge. Making claims about the Creator without evidence is extremely serious. They are attributing to Allah things they have no way of knowing—a grave sin and foolishness."
  },
  69: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Indeed, those who fabricate lies against Allah will never succeed.\"": "Anyone who invents falsehoods about Allah—whether claiming He has children, partners, or any other false attributes—will never achieve true success. They may have temporary gains in this world, but ultimate success (salvation, Paradise, Allah's pleasure) is forever denied to them."
  },
  70: {
    "˹It is only˺ a brief enjoyment in this world,": "Whatever pleasure or success they experience is temporary—a short-lived enjoyment that will soon end. This world's longest life is still brief compared to eternity. Their enjoyment is like a prisoner's last meal before execution.",
    "then to Us is their return,": "After their brief worldly life, they will return to Allah. Death brings them back to their Creator for accounting. There is no escape from this return.",
    "then We will make them taste the severe punishment for their disbelief.": "Upon their return, they will experience intense punishment—a direct consequence of their disbelief and lies about Allah. The word \"taste\" emphasizes that they will feel this punishment fully, experiencing every dimension of its severity."
  },
  71: {
    "Relate to them ˹O Prophet˺ the story of Noah": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to narrate Noah's story to his people. This story contains lessons directly relevant to their situation—a prophet rejected by his people, yet vindicated by Allah.",
    "when he said to his people, \"O my People! If my presence and my reminders to you of Allah's signs are unbearable to you,": "Noah addresses his people with affection (\"my people\") despite their hostility. He acknowledges their frustration with his constant preaching. For centuries, he reminded them of Allah's signs, and they found his presence increasingly intolerable.",
    "then ˹know that˺ I have put my trust in Allah.": "Despite their threats and rejection, Noah declares his complete reliance on Allah. His trust (tawakkul) is unshakeable. He fears Allah alone and depends on Him for protection and success.",
    "So devise a plot along with your associate-gods—and you do not have to be secretive about your plot—then carry it out against me without delay!": "This is a powerful challenge: gather all your forces, human and divine (your idols). Plan openly—no need for secrecy. Execute your best plan against me immediately. Noah is so confident in Allah's protection that he invites them to do their worst. This is the ultimate expression of trust in Allah."
  },
  72: {
    "And if you turn away, ˹remember˺ I have never demanded a reward from you ˹for delivering the message˺.": "Noah reminds them that his motives are pure. He never asked for money, status, or any worldly compensation for his preaching. His message was sincere and selfless—given freely without any expectation of return.",
    "My reward is only from Allah.": "His true payment comes from Allah alone. This is the hallmark of genuine prophets—they seek no worldly gain from their mission. Their only concern is Allah's pleasure and the reward He provides.",
    "And I have been commanded to be one of those who submit ˹to Allah˺.\"": "Noah declares his identity: he is a Muslim—one who submits to Allah's will. This submission defines his entire life. All prophets came with the same essential message of submission to the One God."
  },
  73: {
    "But they still rejected him,": "Despite Noah's sincere preaching for 950 years, his people persisted in disbelief. They refused to abandon their idols and submit to Allah. Their stubbornness sealed their fate.",
    "so We saved him and those with him in the Ark": "When Allah's judgment came, Noah and the believers were protected in the Ark he built under divine guidance. The Ark became their salvation while the world around them was destroyed.",
    "and made them successors,": "After the flood, Noah and the believers inherited the earth. They became the new humanity from whom all subsequent people descended. The disbelievers were erased; the believers continued.",
    "and drowned those who rejected Our signs.": "The Great Flood destroyed everyone who denied Allah's signs. Despite all warnings, they refused to believe, and Allah's punishment swept them away. Water, which sustains life, became the instrument of their death.",
    "See then what was the end of those who had been warned!": "This is a direct address to the Quraysh and all readers: observe the fate of those who received warning and rejected it. The same principle applies in every era. Warning followed by rejection leads to destruction."
  },
  74: {
    "Then after him We sent ˹other˺ messengers to their ˹own˺ people": "After Noah, Allah continued sending prophets to various nations. Each people received their own messenger, speaking their language and understanding their context. Allah's mercy ensured no nation was left without guidance.",
    "and they came to them with clear proofs.": "These messengers brought undeniable evidence—miracles, logical arguments, and divine revelation. The proofs were clear enough to convince any sincere seeker of truth.",
    "But they would not believe in what they had rejected before.": "Despite clear proofs, these nations followed the same pattern as Noah's people. They rejected truth because their ancestors had rejected it. They inherited disbelief and refused to reconsider. Their rejection became a tradition passed down through generations.",
    "This is how We seal the hearts of the transgressors.": "When people persistently transgress and reject truth, Allah seals their hearts as a consequence. This sealing is not arbitrary punishment but the natural result of their choices. They chose to close their hearts repeatedly until Allah made that closure permanent. The transgressors did this to themselves."
  },
  75: {
    "Then after these ˹messengers˺ We sent Moses and Aaron to Pharaoh and his chiefs with Our signs.": "Allah sent two prophets—Moses and his brother Aaron—to Pharaoh and his ruling elite. They carried Allah's signs (miracles and message) to the most powerful ruler of their time. This mission required immense courage.",
    "But they behaved arrogantly": "Pharaoh and his chiefs responded with arrogance. Despite seeing miraculous signs, they refused to humble themselves before Allah's messengers. Their pride prevented them from accepting truth, even when it was undeniable.",
    "and were a wicked people.": "Their arrogance was rooted in wickedness. They were criminals—oppressing the Israelites, claiming divine status for Pharaoh, and rejecting Allah's guidance. Their wickedness and arrogance were intertwined, each reinforcing the other."
  },
  76: {
    "When the truth came to them from Us, they said, \"This is certainly pure magic!\"": "When Moses demonstrated his miracles—the staff becoming a serpent, his hand shining white—Pharaoh's response was dismissal: \"This is obviously magic!\" Rather than accepting the divine origin of these signs, they labeled them as tricks. This was a convenient excuse to reject truth without seriously considering it."
  },
  77: {
    "Moses responded, \"Is this what you say about the truth when it has come to you?": "Moses challenges their accusation: When truth arrives with clear evidence, you call it magic? This response highlights their intellectual dishonesty. They were not genuinely investigating; they were dismissing without consideration.",
    "Is this magic?": "Moses points to the obvious difference between his miracles and magic tricks. Magic is deception; his signs were real transformations that defied natural law. Any honest observer could see the difference.",
    "Magicians will never succeed.\"": "Moses declares a principle: magicians—those who deal in illusion and deception—will never achieve true success. Their tricks may impress temporarily, but they cannot prevail against Allah's truth. This is both a statement of fact and a prophecy about the coming confrontation."
  },
  78: {
    "They argued, \"Have you come to turn us away from the faith of our forefathers": "Pharaoh's chiefs reveal their true concern: preserving ancestral traditions. They followed their fathers' religion not because it was true, but because it was familiar. Change threatened their identity and comfort.",
    "so that the two of you may become supreme in the land?": "They accuse Moses and Aaron of having political motives—seeking power over Egypt. This is projection: they themselves were obsessed with power and assumed everyone else was too. They couldn't fathom that prophets seek only Allah's pleasure, not worldly dominion.",
    "We will never believe in you!\"": "They declare outright rejection. Their minds are closed; no evidence will change them. This stubborn refusal, despite clear signs, demonstrates how arrogance blinds people to truth."
  },
  79: {
    "Pharaoh demanded, \"Bring me every skilled magician.\"": "Pharaoh's strategy was to defeat Moses with magic. If Moses's signs were merely magic (as he claimed), then Egypt's best magicians should be able to match or surpass them. He gathered expert magicians from across his kingdom for a public showdown, confident this would expose Moses as a fraud."
  },
  80: {
    "When the magicians came, Moses said to them, \"Cast whatever you wish to cast!\"": "Moses demonstrates supreme confidence. He lets the magicians go first, giving them every advantage. He is not worried because he knows the difference between magic tricks and Allah's genuine miracles. This confidence comes from trust in Allah, not arrogance."
  },
  81: {
    "When they did, Moses said, \"What you have produced is mere magic,": "After the magicians performed their tricks—making ropes and sticks appear as snakes—Moses identifies their work for what it is: illusion and deception. Despite its impressive appearance, it was just trickery with no reality behind it.",
    "Allah will surely make it useless,": "Moses declares with certainty that Allah will nullify their magic. And indeed, when Moses threw his staff, it became a real serpent that swallowed all their fake snakes. Allah's truth consumed their falsehood.",
    "for Allah certainly does not set right the work of the corruptors.": "Those who spread corruption—whether through magic, deception, or opposing Allah's messengers—will never have their efforts succeed permanently. Allah does not bless the work of those who corrupt the earth. Eventually, their schemes collapse."
  },
  82: {
    "And Allah establishes the truth by His Words—": "Allah makes truth prevail through His decree and His revelation. When Allah decides that truth will triumph, nothing can stop it. His words (commands) bring about what He wills, establishing truth firmly and permanently.",
    "even to the dismay of the wicked.\"": "The criminals and evildoers hate to see truth win. They worked hard to suppress it; they invested in falsehood; they wanted their way to prevail. But despite their hatred and efforts, Allah's truth overcomes all opposition. Their displeasure changes nothing—truth triumphs regardless."
  },
  83: {
    "But no one believed in Moses except a few youths of his people,": "Despite Moses's clear miracles and compelling message, only a small group of young people from the Israelites believed in him initially. The elders, perhaps more set in their ways or more fearful of consequences, held back. Youth often have less to lose and more courage to embrace truth.",
    "while fearing that Pharaoh and their own chiefs might persecute them.": "Even these few believers lived in constant fear. They worried about persecution from two sources: Pharaoh's regime and their own Israelite leaders who might report them or punish them for following Moses. Faith under such oppression requires extraordinary courage.",
    "And certainly Pharaoh was a tyrant in the land,": "Pharaoh's tyranny was extreme—he claimed divinity, enslaved an entire people, and killed infant boys. His oppression was comprehensive, controlling every aspect of life in Egypt. Living under such a ruler made open faith nearly impossible.",
    "and he was truly a transgressor.": "Pharaoh exceeded all limits in his crimes. He was not just a harsh ruler but a transgressor against Allah Himself—claiming to be god, persecuting believers, and corrupting the land. His transgression knew no bounds."
  },
  84: {
    "Moses said, \"O my people! If you do believe in Allah and submit ˹to His Will˺,": "Moses addresses his frightened followers with a condition: if your faith in Allah is genuine, and if you have truly submitted to Him as Muslims (those who submit), then certain behavior should follow.",
    "then put your trust in Him.\"": "The natural consequence of true faith is tawakkul—complete reliance on Allah. If you believe Allah is All-Powerful and that He controls all affairs, then you should trust Him with your fears and difficulties. Fear of Pharaoh should not paralyze believers who trust in the Lord of all creation."
  },
  85: {
    "They replied, \"In Allah we trust.": "The believers respond positively to Moses's call, declaring their trust in Allah. This is the response of true faith—hearing guidance and immediately applying it.",
    "Our Lord! Do not subject us to the persecution of the oppressive people,": "They immediately turn to Allah in prayer, asking Him not to make them a trial (fitnah) for the wrongdoers. This could mean: don't let them defeat us (which would make them think they're right), don't let them torture us, or don't let our situation become a test that leads others astray. They seek Allah's protection through supplication."
  },
  86: {
    "and deliver us by Your mercy from the disbelieving people.\"": "They ask Allah for salvation from the disbelievers through His mercy. They don't claim to deserve rescue based on their own merit; they appeal to Allah's mercy. This humble supplication acknowledges that deliverance comes from Allah's grace, not human effort alone."
  },
  87: {
    "We revealed to Moses and his brother, \"Appoint houses for your people in Egypt.": "Allah gave practical guidance during this difficult time. The believers needed safe spaces in Egypt where they could gather. These houses would serve as sanctuaries during the oppression.",
    "Turn these houses into places of worship,": "These homes should face the qiblah (direction of prayer) and serve as mosques—places dedicated to worshipping Allah. When public worship is dangerous, private homes become sacred spaces. This teaches that worship continues even under persecution.",
    "establish prayer,": "Prayer must be maintained regardless of circumstances. Even facing Pharaoh's tyranny, the command to pray remains. Prayer connects believers to Allah, gives them strength, and keeps their faith alive during hardship.",
    "and give good news to the believers!\"": "Despite the current suffering, Moses and Aaron should encourage the believers with glad tidings. Allah's help is coming; their patience will be rewarded; Pharaoh's reign will end. Good news sustains hope during dark times."
  },
  88: {
    "Moses prayed, \"Our Lord! You have granted Pharaoh and his chiefs luxuries and riches in this worldly life,": "Moses observes that Allah has given Pharaoh immense wealth, adornments, and worldly power. This is not a complaint but an acknowledgment of reality. Allah gives worldly blessings even to disbelievers as a test.",
    "˹which they abused˺ to lead people astray from Your Way!": "Instead of using these blessings to show gratitude and guide others to truth, Pharaoh used his power and wealth to mislead people. His resources became tools of oppression and disbelief. The blessings that should have brought him closer to Allah pushed him further away.",
    "Our Lord, destroy their riches": "Moses asks Allah to obliterate their wealth—to make it useless or cursed. This is not personal vengeance but a prayer that the tools of oppression be removed. Some scholars say this prayer was answered when their wealth was turned to stone or became useless.",
    "and harden their hearts so that they will not believe until they see the painful punishment.\"": "This is a severe prayer, made after exhausting all peaceful options. Pharaoh and his chiefs had rejected every sign and every opportunity. Moses, by divine inspiration, prays that their hearts be sealed and that they only believe when facing destruction—at which point belief no longer benefits. This prayer came after centuries of patient preaching met with stubborn rejection."
  },
  89: {
    "Allah responded ˹to Moses and Aaron˺, \"Your prayer is answered!": "Allah confirms that the supplication of Moses (and Aaron, who said 'Ameen') has been accepted. The destruction of Pharaoh and his regime is decreed. This shows the power of sincere prayer, especially from the oppressed.",
    "So be steadfast": "Despite the answered prayer, they must remain firm and continue their mission. The answer may not manifest immediately—there could be a gap between acceptance and execution. During this waiting period, steadfastness is essential.",
    "and do not follow the way of those who do not know.\"": "Allah warns them not to adopt the behavior of the ignorant—those who lose patience, compromise their principles, or abandon their mission. Even when victory is promised, believers must maintain their path and not imitate those without knowledge."
  },
  90: {
    "We brought the Children of Israel across the sea.": "Allah parted the sea for the Israelites, creating a miraculous path through which they crossed safely. This was one of the greatest miracles—water standing like walls while an entire nation walked on dry ground between them.",
    "Then Pharaoh and his soldiers pursued them unjustly and oppressively.": "Driven by arrogance and hatred, Pharaoh led his army after the Israelites. His pursuit was motivated by transgression and oppression—he could not accept that his slaves had escaped. His pride pushed him into the sea after them.",
    "But as Pharaoh was drowning, he cried out, \"I believe that there is no god except that in whom the Children of Israel believe,": "When the water crashed down upon Pharaoh and death became certain, he suddenly declared faith. The same Pharaoh who claimed to be god now acknowledges the God of the Israelites. The arrogant tyrant becomes desperate.",
    "and I am ˹now˺ one of those who submit.\"": "Pharaoh claims to be a Muslim—one who submits to Allah. These words, which would have saved him had they come earlier, are now uttered only because death is upon him. His 'faith' is not sincere conviction but desperate survival instinct."
  },
  91: {
    "˹He was told,˺ \"Now ˹you believe˺?": "This response drips with divine rebuke. Now you believe? At this moment, when no other option remains? Where was this faith when you saw the miracles? When Moses performed sign after sign?",
    "But you always disobeyed and were one of the corruptors.": "Throughout his life, Pharaoh consistently disobeyed Allah, persecuted believers, and spread corruption in the land. His track record is one of unrelenting evil. This final moment 'faith' cannot erase a lifetime of deliberate transgression. Faith at the moment of death, when one sees the punishment, is not accepted—the door closes when death arrives."
  },
  92: {
    "Today We will preserve your corpse": "Although Pharaoh drowned, Allah decreed that his body would be preserved—not as honor but as evidence. While his soul faced punishment, his body would serve a purpose for future generations.",
    "so that you may become an example for those who come after you.": "Pharaoh's preserved body stands as a lesson for humanity. Those who see it should reflect: this is what remains of the man who claimed to be god, who challenged Allah's messenger, who oppressed an entire nation. His mummy, discovered in modern times, confirms this Quranic statement made 1400 years ago.",
    "And surely most people are heedless of Our examples!\"": "Despite clear signs like Pharaoh's preserved corpse, most people remain oblivious. They visit museums, see the evidence, yet fail to take the lesson. Heedlessness prevents people from benefiting from even the most obvious signs."
  },
  93: {
    "Indeed, We settled the Children of Israel in a blessed land,": "After their rescue from Egypt, Allah established the Israelites in a blessed land—the Holy Land of Palestine and surrounding areas. They went from slavery to inheritance of a promised, fertile territory.",
    "and granted them good, lawful provisions.": "Allah provided them with wholesome, permissible sustenance. They had pure food, comfortable living, and divine blessings. Their material needs were fully met.",
    "They did not differ until knowledge came to them.": "Initially, they were united. Their divisions and disputes arose only after they received knowledge—the Torah and clear teachings. Ironically, knowledge that should have united them became a source of division due to misinterpretation, jealousy, and desire for worldly gain. They argued about scripture while knowing the truth.",
    "Surely your Lord will judge between them on the Day of Judgment regarding their differences.": "Their disputes will be resolved by Allah on the Day of Judgment. He will clarify who was right, who was wrong, and dispense perfect justice. This postponed judgment allows time for repentance while guaranteeing ultimate accountability."
  },
  94: {
    "If you ˹O Prophet˺ are in doubt about ˹these stories˺ that We have revealed to you,": "This is a hypothetical address. The Prophet ﷺ was never in doubt, but the verse addresses any potential skepticism about the Quranic narratives. If any doubt existed (which it didn't), there is a way to verify.",
    "then ask those who read the Scripture before you.": "The People of the Book—Jews and Christians—possess earlier scriptures that confirm these stories. Their Torah contains accounts of Moses, Pharaoh, and the Israelites. This verification shows continuity between revelations and proves the Quran's authenticity.",
    "The truth has certainly come to you from your Lord,": "This is absolute confirmation: what you have received is truth from Allah. It is not fabrication, not borrowing from earlier sources, but genuine revelation from the Lord of all worlds.",
    "so do not be one of those who doubt,": "The Prophet ﷺ is urged never to entertain doubt. This command extends to all believers: having received clear truth, doubt is inappropriate. Certainty should characterize the believer's faith."
  },
  95: {
    "and do not be one of those who deny Allah's signs": "Beyond avoiding doubt, one must never deny Allah's signs—whether Quranic verses, natural phenomena, or historical events that point to truth. Denial is a step beyond doubt, representing active rejection.",
    "or you will be one of the losers.": "Those who deny Allah's signs join the ranks of losers—those who have failed the test of life and forfeited eternal success. This stark warning emphasizes the gravity of rejection."
  },
  96: {
    "Indeed, those against whom Allah's decree ˹of torment˺ is justified will not believe—": "Some people, through their persistent rejection and hardened hearts, have earned Allah's decree against them. Once this decree is established—after they have exhausted all opportunities—they become incapable of faith. This is a consequence of their choices, not arbitrary predestination."
  },
  97: {
    "even if every sign were to come to them—until they see the painful punishment.": "Even if every possible miracle appeared before them—signs from heaven, undeniable proofs, supernatural events—they still would not believe. Their hearts are sealed. Only when punishment actually descends will they acknowledge the truth, but by then it's too late, as with Pharaoh."
  },
  98: {
    "If only there had been a society which believed ˹before seeing the torment˺ and, therefore, benefited from its belief,": "Throughout history, nations only believed when destruction was upon them—too late for faith to benefit them. Allah expresses a wish that some community had believed earlier, when belief would have saved them.",
    "like the people of Jonah.": "One exception exists: the people of Nineveh, to whom Prophet Jonah (Yunus) was sent. When they saw signs of approaching punishment, they repented sincerely before it arrived—not during it. Their belief came in time.",
    "When they believed, We lifted from them the torment of disgrace in this world": "Because they repented genuinely before punishment descended, Allah removed the impending disaster. The clouds of destruction dispersed, and they were spared the humiliation other nations faced. This shows Allah's mercy: sincere, timely repentance is accepted.",
    "and allowed them enjoyment for a while.": "They were given extended life to enjoy—time to live, worship, and benefit from their faith. This 'while' refers to their remaining lifespan and that of their descendants. They became an example of how communities can be saved through collective repentance."
  },
  99: {
    "Had your Lord so willed ˹O Prophet˺, all ˹people˺ on earth would have certainly believed, every single one of them!": "If Allah wanted, He could have made everyone believe—He could have created humans without free will or compelled universal faith. His power is absolute; this would have been easy for Him.",
    "Would you then force people to become believers?": "Given that Allah Himself chose not to force belief, how could you, O Prophet, compel it? Faith must be voluntary to be meaningful. Forced belief is no belief at all. The Prophet's role is to convey, not to coerce. This verse establishes religious freedom as a divine principle—there is no compulsion in religion."
  },
  100: {
    "It is not for any soul to believe except by Allah's leave,": "Faith requires Allah's permission and facilitation. No one believes independently of Allah's will. This doesn't mean Allah prevents willing hearts from believing; rather, Allah enables those who sincerely seek guidance. The door to faith opens by Allah's grace.",
    "and He will bring His wrath upon those who are unmindful.": "Those who refuse to use their intellect—who ignore signs, reject evidence, and remain heedless—face Allah's anger. Being unmindful is a choice; they could think and reflect but choose not to. This willful ignorance earns divine displeasure."
  },
  101: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Consider all that is in the heavens and the earth!\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is told to invite people to observe and reflect on creation. Look at the stars, the sun, the moon; examine the earth, the mountains, the oceans; study plants, animals, and human beings. Evidence of Allah is everywhere for those willing to see.",
    "Yet neither signs nor warners are of any benefit to those who refuse to believe.": "Despite countless signs in creation and numerous prophets who warned them, some people remain unmoved. Signs don't help those determined to disbelieve. Warners cannot benefit hearts that are sealed. The problem is not lack of evidence but refusal to accept it."
  },
  102: {
    "Are they waiting for ˹anything˺ except the same torments that befell those before them?": "Do the disbelievers expect something different from what happened to previous nations? Are they waiting for floods, earthquakes, or destruction like the people of Noah, 'Ad, and Thamud faced? History's pattern is clear.",
    "Say, \"Keep waiting then! I too am waiting with you.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ tells them to continue waiting if they wish. He, too, waits—but he waits for Allah's promise of victory and their punishment. The believers wait with confidence; the disbelievers wait unknowingly for their doom."
  },
  103: {
    "Then We saved Our messengers and those who believed.": "When destruction came to past nations, Allah always saved His messengers and the believers. Noah was saved in the Ark; Lot escaped Sodom; Moses crossed the sea. The pattern never fails—Allah protects His own.",
    "For it is Our duty to save the believers.": "Allah has made it binding upon Himself (though nothing is obligatory upon Him) to rescue the believers. This is His promise, His commitment, His self-imposed duty born from mercy. Believers can trust that Allah will not abandon them when calamity strikes."
  },
  104: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O humanity! If you are in doubt of my faith,": "The Prophet ﷺ addresses all people: if you have any confusion about what I believe and practice, let me make it absolutely clear.",
    "then ˹know that˺ I do not worship those ˹idols˺ you worship instead of Allah.": "I absolutely reject the worship of anything besides Allah—no idols, no false gods, no partners. This is a clear line that cannot be crossed or compromised.",
    "But I worship Allah, Who has the power to cause your death.": "I worship only Allah—the One who controls life and death, who will eventually cause you all to die. This attribute reminds them of Allah's ultimate power and their inevitable return to Him.",
    "And I have been commanded, 'Be one of the believers,'": "My worship of Allah alone is not my personal choice but divine command. I have been ordered to be among the believers—those who accept truth and submit to Allah."
  },
  105: {
    "and, 'Be steadfast in faith in all uprightness,": "I have been commanded to turn my face—my entire being—toward the religion with complete devotion and sincerity. 'Hanif' means inclining toward truth, away from all falsehood. This is unwavering, wholehearted commitment.",
    "and do not be one of the polytheists,'": "I have been explicitly forbidden from any form of shirk—associating partners with Allah. This prohibition is absolute and defines my entire identity and mission."
  },
  106: {
    "and 'Do not invoke, instead of Allah, what can neither benefit nor harm you—": "Do not call upon anything that has no power to help you or hurt you. Idols, dead saints, jinn—none of these can truly benefit or harm. Only Allah possesses real power.",
    "for if you do, then you will certainly be one of the wrongdoers,'": "If you worship powerless beings, you wrong yourself by wasting your devotion, you wrong Allah by giving His rights to others, and you wrong the truth by following falsehood. Polytheism is injustice in its worst form."
  },
  107: {
    "and 'If Allah touches you with harm, none can undo it except Him.": "When Allah decrees difficulty for you—illness, loss, suffering—no one else can remove it. Doctors treat, but Allah cures. Friends console, but Allah relieves. All help ultimately comes from Him.",
    "And if He intends good for you, none can withhold His bounty.": "Conversely, when Allah decides to bless you, no force can prevent it. Enemies cannot block your provision; obstacles cannot stop your success if Allah wills it. His bounty reaches whom He chooses.",
    "He grants it to whoever He wills of His servants.": "Allah's blessings are distributed according to His wisdom. He knows who deserves what and when. His choices are always perfect, even when we don't understand them.",
    "And He is the All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.'\"": "Despite human weakness and sin, Allah forgives abundantly and shows endless mercy. These beautiful names offer hope: no matter what you've done, Allah's forgiveness and mercy are available to those who turn to Him."
  },
  108: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O humanity! The truth has surely come to you from your Lord.": "This is a universal announcement: truth has arrived. The Quran has come, the Prophet has been sent, and the message is clear. No one can claim ignorance; the truth is now accessible to all humanity.",
    "So whoever chooses to be guided, it is only for their own good.": "Those who accept guidance benefit themselves. Their faith saves their own soul; their good deeds fill their own account. Guidance is a personal treasure that enriches only the one who embraces it.",
    "And whoever chooses to stray, it is only to their own loss.": "Those who reject guidance harm themselves. Their disbelief destroys their own afterlife; their sins burden their own record. Allah is not diminished by their rejection; they alone suffer the consequences.",
    "And I am not a keeper over you.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is not responsible for forcing people to believe or controlling their choices. His role is to deliver the message clearly—which he has done perfectly. Each person must decide for themselves; the Prophet is not their guardian or controller."
  },
  109: {
    "And follow what is revealed to you,": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to remain faithful to revelation. In the face of rejection, mockery, and hardship, his duty is to stick to what Allah reveals. This command extends to all Muslims: follow the Quran and authentic Sunnah, not personal opinions or popular trends.",
    "and be patient until Allah passes His judgment.": "Patience is essential. Victory, vindication, and justice may not come immediately. The Prophet ﷺ must wait for Allah's timing. This patience is active—continuing the mission while trusting Allah's plan. The same applies to all believers facing difficulty.",
    "For He is the Best of Judges.": "Allah's judgment is perfect—better than any human decision or earthly court. He knows all circumstances, all intentions, and all consequences. When His judgment comes, it will be perfectly fair, wise, and final. This truth provides comfort during waiting and confidence in ultimate justice."
  }
};